#FileNotExists Exception in sqoop import command used with Target-Dir argument

When we use target-dir argument in sqoop import command, the directory specified should not be created earlier. It should be a non existent directory. This is beacuse sqoop creates a new directory at the path specified in the target-dir argument.

Whereas when we use warehouse-dir argument, we should specify the path of a pre-existent directory. Sqoop treats this path as a parent directory and creates subsequent directory with the name of the table import within the parent directory.
Therefore warehouse-dir is generally used with sqoop-import-all command. We specify a parent directory and a directory is then created for each table within the parent directory.

Example - 

sqoop import \
--connect jdbc:mysql://quickstart.cloudera:3306/retail_db \
--username cloudera \
--password cloudera \
--table departments \
--target-dir /user/cloudera/departments 

#/user/cloudera/departments should not be present already


sqoop-import-all \
--connect jdbc:mysql://quickstart.cloudera:3306/retail_db \
--username cloudera \
--password cloudera \
--table departments \
--warehouse-dir /user/cloudera/imported_tables 

# /user/cloudera/imported_tables is the patrent directory. Within it, different directories will be created like 

/user/cloudera/imported_tables/departments
/user/cloudera/imported_tables/categories
/user/cloudera/imported_tables/orders
.
.
.
.
